segments.text: This is Debbie Park interviewing Mr. D.A.
Anderson at Mr. Anderson's home for the history of the City of College Station Project, September 22nd, 1983, Side 1.
I'd like to start with some background information.
Where were you born?
Well, I was born in Pittston, Pennsylvania, P-I-T-T-S-T-O-N. That's in the northeastern part of the state, in the anthracite region.
It's a small town not far from the Pocono Mountains.
And I spent quite a bit of time in the Poconos as a youth, you know, in the mountains.
And that is one reason, I think, why my vocation
trees today.
Actually, I had two choices.
One was medicine and the other was forestry.
And they both had an equal tug in my heart, but apparently forestry won out and that was why I majored in forestry at Penn State University.
Well, were your parents from Pennsylvania also
My mother was born there, but my father came from Scarborough.
And as a youth, he came while I guess he was about 21, 22 years old.
And came to the area, married my mother.
And then he, well, he started to work in the coal fields.
He rose to the rank of a foreman.
He was a good worker.
I, myself, also worked in the mines during the summer.
Matter of fact, I carry a piece of coal right there.
I've never wanted to take it out.
That fell out of the roof one day.
Oh, my gosh.
And you can see it.
Oh, you sure can.
Oh, my gosh.
But it reminds you of your... Well, that's why I carry it.
It's a memento of when I worked in the forest.
Well, you mentioned a minute ago about your education.
You went to the university or something?
No, not the university.
I went to Penn State University.
Penn State.
Yeah.
And majored in forestry?
And majored in forestry.
And did you work on... Well, actually, even though I went to Penn State, they had an area...
in southern Pennsylvania where they screened out potential foresters.
And the first two years you went all year.
Summer you had your ordinary curriculum.
You were staying in a dormitory and you were subject to firefighting, you were subject to anything that arose in terms of the forest.
They had a
nursery there, and you had to work in the nursery.
In other words, they had two years, or anyone that went into forestry spent two years doing a lot of distasteful work.
In other words, unless you liked it, you wouldn't stay.
And they made it hard, both in coursework and otherwise.
For example, we had what we called, in that day, Boy Scout merit patches.
I mean, we were inclined to call them that.
But we had to know, I think, 30 constellations in the sky.
In other words, as people in forestry, this was part of it.
We had to know every, we called them bugs, insects.

that were flying around the campus or you know to identify all the insects that were common to the forest area or the city common names and scientific names this was on the side we had to know every rock you know a fellow professor pull up a rock or pick up a rock in the area and we had to know the type of rock this was all a prelude to
other formal education too.
We had to know, we had to have leaf collections, we had to have grass collections, we had to know the sounds of all the birds.
We had to know all the birds.
In other words, they were making environmentalists really out of us.
Is the education different today?
Oh yes, by far, right.
And even when you
When I took the civil service to get into federal civil service, it lasted three days.
And I had to know how to put a telephone together and take it apart.
I had to know telephone lines, transposition, because being in the Forest Service, well, you had to do with communications.
So we didn't have radios in these days.
So you had to know the communication system.
And they just threw everything at you.
And as I said, I think there were 91 starting out in our class, and only seven graduated.
Oh my God.
Yeah.
Well, would you say that you gained more information than what they do today?
Oh yeah, by far.
I doubt seriously any of them would know the birds or could go outside and call any constellation any season of the year.
You know, where is north?
And things of this nature.
And engineering, why they just stacked it on and stacked it on.
I could lay out railroad curves in my freshman year, almost in my sleep.
We had to go out and estimate the ties, the number of ties per mile.
You know, on the railroad track, everything, and at the bridge, make bridge designs.
It's amazing, the training they put you through in the early days.
And even then, you know, I had to have two years of Latin before I, in high school, before they would accept me at the university.
Well, I'm in favor of that type of an education.
It's a very well-rounded type.
Oh, yeah.
How did you get involved in the Texas Forest Service?
Well, I started out in Pennsylvania.
Following graduation, I worked with the then Division of Plant Industry in the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
This was in the control of a disease that affects white pine, a tree, white pine.
And the alternate host of this disease is what is called ribes, R-I-B-E-S.
It's a currant or a gooseberry.
Maybe you like them, I don't know.
Do you ever eat currants or gooseberries?
Okay.
With this alternate host, I mean the disease spreads from the currant or gooseberry to the pine, where it produces whole postules on the tree and eventually will kill the tree.
And the only way to allow the tree to grow is to get rid of that alternate host, which is the ribes.
So I was detailed.
to travel all over the state of Pennsylvania making recommendations in CCC camps for the control of the ribies.
And I was doing that when the opportunity came up to come to Texas with the U.S. Forest Service.
So I came with the U.S. Forest Service.
To me, I mean, just coming to Texas
You know, that was just, that was a thing.
I mean, that was great to me.
And being, you know, somewhat of a pioneer anyhow, I thought this was great.
So I came down to Texas, and when I came here, I had passed a civil service exam, but they didn't have any civil service openings.
So I was working in the CCC program and other programs of the Forest Service without really a...
civil service, you know, I wasn't in a civil service job.
All of them were filled up.
But then there was an opening occurred up in Channing and Stratford in the soil conservation service.
So my wife and I bundled up.
It was in the middle of the summer.
And we went up there to Channing and Stratford.
I don't know whether you have ever been up there in July.
You could just see that, you know, that heat emanate from that ground.
There were no trees.
You know, it was just a desolate area.
So I turned around and came back to the piney woods of East Texas.
I was at that time in Lufkin.
Well then when I came back, there was an opening in the Texas Forest Service.
So
I wanted something a little bit more permanent than to be an employee out here.
Had I stayed, everything would have worked out all right.
But I was taking a chance because all the appointed offices were filled up.
So I went with the Texas Forest Service, which is a part of the A&M system.
And having gone with them, well, I stayed with them for that period.
And were you stationed in College Station?
No, I started out really in Lufkin.
With the Texas Forest Service?
With the Texas Forest Service and I was there through 38 and then came over here and have been here ever since.
And was there a time that you became involved with the educational program of the Texas Forest Service?
Yeah, that's right.
Well, that came later.
yeah well yeah there was established in Texas well we had a part in it I guess a committee for conservation education it was eventually sponsored by the Texas Education Agency and I was named
to this particular committee by Edgar, who was then the head of the education department in Austin.
And I served on that committee for years and years and years.
Actually, I was president of the appointed group for two terms.
And every summer, I went up to various colleges and universities throughout the state of Texas.
I really miss it, you know, today, working with in-service and pre-service teachers in the area of conservation education resource use.
My particular field was plants, grass, trees, you know, any green thing.
And then there was one that dealt with oil and gas.
There was one with soils and one with wildlife, for example.
And I would go into the classroom or auditorium.
I had an experience there, too.
And then work with the teachers.
Now, it all depended on the particular program at the university.
Sometimes I would go and lecture for most of the day and then be available the following day or maybe that afternoon for the development of work units, teaching units that were used in the classroom.
Well, what years were you talking about that you were doing this?
Oh, they were in the 60s and 70s, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, just like the Extension Service.
Any extension service throughout Texas?
No, no, no.
Extension service is just like the Forest Service.
In other words, it is part of the system.
Of the A&M system?
Of the A&M system.
Is there an extension service of, say... No, there's an extension service.
Agricultural Extension Service is a different group, a different organization.
Then there's the Engineering Extension Service.
And see, the fireman's training course, fireman's training comes under engineering extension.
Then there's engineering experiment station.
But the Texas Forest Service or the whole state of Texas is part of the university.
Of A&M?
Yeah.
I didn't realize that.
Yeah.
Well, then, was 38 the year that you came to college here?
It was late 38, 39, yeah.
So you were here...
The city started in 38.
It was 39.
I came just after the whole thing, you know, got started.
Right, okay.
So you were here quite a number of years before you... Oh, yeah, yeah, right.
Well, why did you decide to go to the city council the first time?
Well, some issues came up.
A lot of the citizens, some issues came up.
They weren't maybe, you know, worth shaking in the community.
But they asked me if I would go before the council on their behalf and do thus and so, which I did.
And it became a habit.
If anything else came up, well, Andy, why don't you go?
You're our, you know, our representative.
So finally came around to an election, and they said, well, you'd be better on the council.
You know what I mean.
Rather than going before the council, you can represent us better.
So with that in mind, I did run with their support for the council.
Were these mainly neighbors?
Oh, yeah.
All of College Hills and all around, yeah.
Well, when you got on the council those first couple of years, did you have anything that you were really interested in working on or a project that you were interested in starting?
Well, the main issue at that time among the people, I think, in most of the subdivisions were the subdivision regulations, the deed restrictions.
These developers had these deed restrictions, and they had them registered in court.
They were all nice, and you ran them over, and they were just great.
I mean, the distance between buildings will be 10 feet, and no one will do this or that or the other thing.
But then you found that they didn't adhere to that themselves.
You know what I mean.
When they put up a house, they didn't adhere to some of this.
And then the city, for a while, got to the point, this is one reason why I got involved, was, well, now, for example, the deed restrictions said 10 feet between your property line and your house.
It had to be on both sides, which made for 20 feet, which I like, personally.
But the city regulation was 5 feet.
That means that somebody could live 10 feet away.
You open your blind in the morning, somebody, you know what I mean.
So we had some problems here.
And the city was willing to go ahead and allow somebody to build a house on the lot and build it almost to the property line.
So this was really a problem that we had to fight in the early days.
Now, a lot of this, you know, stems from who was on the council, you know, not necessarily when it started because they were primarily university people.
But boy, yeah, I hate to mention his name, but I could tell you a lot of things.
Well, I'm going to take that.
All right.
Well, if you, whatever you want to say, you can hang out later.
Don't feel like it's something that will be in a record.
That was really, I mean, in the early days, this was a concern to people, you know.
Well, the city did have subdivision ordinances.
Were they allowing people to go past those?
Well, no, they lived up to the city ordinance, but not to the deans.
It wouldn't enforce the deans.
Right.
Well, they did after a while.
When I got on the council, then we started to respect the deed restrictions.
Oh, no, he wanted to make all the money he could.
I mean, that was his primary.
He didn't care if people had to park in the park.
Excuse me.
So the people who were interested in real estate, I guess, were into selling, buying real estate.
Well, they were selling homes or building homes.
You know what I mean?
They didn't particularly care about regulations.
And this is what prompted me, really, to get into city politics.
And then I served for six years.
And I figured, well, now that's enough.
I'll just get out.
So I made up my mind that I'd just drop out.
And then, well, why, Andy, why can't you serve two years on planning and zoning?
I mean, that isn't, well, that was worse almost.
So I served two years on planning and zoning.
In the meantime, the people, particularly all the way back here,
insisted then that I run for mayor.
And I mean, I had up here on the hill.
Well, they knew then if I got in, you know, they'd have some, they could knock on my door and have some control.
So, yeah, so then I served six years on the council, two years on planning and zoning, and then five years as mayor.
Well, when you first got on the council, Mayor Lankford had been the mayor for quite a few years.
A good many years, right.
And he was also continuing for some more time.
And can you describe the philosophy that he employed as mayor, what he was interested in?
Well, we were all interested, I think.
We were interested.
a very conservative, at that time, council.
Federal aid was brought in the land.
And all of us, of course, serving on that council, came up through the Depression.
I did myself as a boy.
You know what I mean.
I was a product of the Depression.
I went to school at the university through the Depression.
I know what the school of hard knocks is.
I came up on the other side of the track.
What I mean by that, I never had much as a child because of, you know what I mean, the economic conditions existing.
And I scratched around for everything to go to the university.
And if I could, well, I knew others could do the same thing.
I did everything.
You know what I mean?
Shoe laces, shoe polish, I did everything to get a little bit.
I ate a lot of bread for meals, too.
I mean, I didn't... You know, bread was maybe my breakfast or dinner, see?
You know what I mean?
You just don't have it.
You have to get by, and you work harder to get another nickel to do something else.
And I went through the hard way, and I think everybody on that council...
you know, had that spirit of, you know, if you pull yourself up by your heels, there were a lot of federal projects in the area we didn't particularly want.
And we thought, well, we ought to earn them ourselves.
Do it ourselves.
Let's not call on the federal government to do it.
Well, this was, I think this was the theme during most of Lankford's tenure.
Then I think the thinking began, I myself changed.
You know what I mean?
Well, now here is Brian getting it.
Here is everybody all over the state getting it.
We're sending our taxes, and we're not getting anything in return.
So I think after life, then there was a change in the philosophy on the council, whereby then we'll go out after some of these things.

and i know the sewage disposal plant i know was one and of course the fellow that was heading up hued at that time was an aggie that was an easy one we we had some disappointments personally i have we were well i'll say it but i had arranged to have the
this creek down here, channelized from the apartments clear through to McCarter Creek as a federal project.
Now this was done through a number of good friends in the Soil Conservation Service and otherwise, clear through to the Washington office.
This was

in the Washington office and had been approved, you know, now my application had been put on top of the pile through some friends and had been approved and was ready to leave Washington and come down whereby this whole area would have been channelized.
And Glenn Cook out at the VVDC

raised the question that it was not approved at the local level and therefore had to be thrown out and he ruined that whole project because of his attitude towards that there was no way that you could locally improve it at this point well yeah i could have gone through but then i would have been in the bottom of the pile see i ran through french to get in the top of the pile in washington
And Eddie called me up and said, Andy, what's this all about?
Or, you know, to help me rather than just turn it down.
And so, did the city ever channelize it?
No.
No, I didn't think so.
No.
You know, it's just plain ditch now.
We'd have had all them federal funds just to...
Well, it would be a HUD project.
But it's just one of these things that you wish that something else had transpired, because that would have been, in terms of drainage,
Even today, in a way, it hasn't totally drained the way it should be drained.
Well, it's a shame that the project would have been so worthwhile, and it's inhibited because it's here for one of the wrong reasons, I guess.
Right, right.
That's not in the record either, I don't think.
Oh, is that right?
I hadn't read about that.
What did you see as advantages or disadvantages for the city of College Station having a mayor, the same mayor, for 24 years?
You served many years.
Well, I didn't, Lankford was, yeah, I served many years with Lankford.
You know, during his tenure, the city was in the formative stages.
developing.
If you look back and see some of the old ordinances that were drawn up, they're quite interesting.
They wouldn't hold water legally today, you know, the way some of them were drawn up.
But it was a formative government.
I think it was university controlled.
for the most part, until the boyhood got in, the faction got in.
It had to be.
It was just like the school, you know.
The school was on the campus at that time, and then it moved over to the chicken coops, as we called it.
I don't know what else to say.
I think that...
Well, everybody, everyone was really, I think, very well satisfied with the form of government, for the most part.
Ernest never, he went in each election.
Sure, he had some people against him, which is natural.
But he went in with a fair-sized majority, and people were satisfied in that period.
see the number, you know, the population.
You know, when I came here, this was just nothing but a cotton field, you know, for the most part.
This is one of the oldest houses in the area.
In the area?
Yeah.
And when did you build this?
This was built in late 37 and 38 by Ross Sherwood, who was head of the poultry department.
And I bought the house from him.
Oh, my God.
And that was a lot of money.
No, I've added a lot to it.
You know, I've added a room in the back here and added still further on in the back so that when the children can come, like, you know, they have their own bath and accommodations.
A lot more room.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Well, when you were on the council, it seems as though a lot of time was spent working out street repair and street building.
Do you remember?
Oh, yeah.
There were those that wanted to, some few, that wanted to, wanted the city to issue, well, they wanted to get a big bond issued
to pave all the streets.
And again, that conservatism in us showed up.
And we got our pencils out, and we figured we could do a better job on a pay-as-you-go basis.
And you probably read about that in whatever you read.
And we went to the people in total support of a pay-as-you-go program.
and they endorsed it by an overwhelming majority.
I don't think we needed to spend the money, you know what I mean, millions of dollars just to repair all the streets.
I think we did a very creditable job the other way and saved the city much money.
As you look back, do you think the decision was the best?
Right, I do, right.
Do you think the city might have gotten into a debt that is... Well, a debt there, yeah.
And of course, you've got to keep in mind the philosophy of the... You know what I mean?
We went through a depression.
I know what a dollar is.
And today, well, I'm going to save that dollar for the city.
And then throughout my regime, when I was mayor, I squeezed everything that I could to get a maximum out of that dollar.
Because I prided myself on trying to get a maximum return on every dollar we spent.
And unless I figured we were going to get a return, that was something else.
Also, there was a period when the city was trying to build an underpass at Crompton Market Road 60 in Wilbur.
And it began in the 50s.
They started talking about it, but it wasn't completed until the early 60s.
I was wondering if you had any thoughts as to why it was so delayed and what happened with those.
You mean the overpass?
Overpass, right.
Yeah.
At the railroad track.
Yeah, because you don't mean the one at Boyette.
Yeah.
At University Drive?
Right.
Yeah.
Well, that's the one where I used the voting procedure to get him to vote in favor of something.
This had come up at several meetings.
You've read the minutes.
It came up.
several meetings in an attempt to get Boyette and his followers to endorse, you know, the underpass.
And he wouldn't do it because of the condemnation procedures against his land.
And he did not think they were fair and all kinds of things.
The minutes are replete with this information.
And the judge, Judge Bill Davis at the time,
He was chomping at the bits, and the highway department had the money, and they were ready to go, and everything was held up because of the situation.
And that is when we, well, we arranged to at least try Robert's Rules of Water.
And we were fortunate in raising it two degrees and then coming back twice, or coming back

quickly and uh in the process you know unless you keep your mind about you you don't know what what's going on so we got him to vote in favor so up until this point the council had not approved no city taking part in in the condemnation no no no he held everything up
And it was through this Robert Shultz Award that we got him mixed up.
Well, was he afraid that he wouldn't get enough money from the condemnation group?
Oh, yeah.
He wanted a lot more.
Oh, I see.
He wanted a lot more, and they wouldn't allow any more.
See, they met, and the condemnation group met, and made this award.
And that was really the tops.
They made him an offer and everything else, yeah.
I forget, you know, the details, but he was well aware of what he was going to get, and it was beyond what other people normally thought was justified.
But he, you know, he had that, well, cold beer,
Oh, yeah.
It was taken down to put in.
Oh, he didn't want to see that taken down?
Well, yeah.
He said that was worth a million dollars.
You know, all them kind of stories.
For example, we only paid $175,000 to Louis Mays for the intersection down here at University and Highway 6.
you know, right down across Caddy Corner from the golf station.
And that was a more valuable piece of land than, boy, yes, you know, a little track up there.
But I thought he was offering more than enough for what he had there.
And then when you realize what he did get out of the churches and the business people, you know, and how he got to the students, I...
I'm just full of stories.
Well, I had heard that there's a lot of things that happened also, building very, very small apartments, I think, for students that didn't meet the restrictions or didn't meet the conditions.
No.
Well, see, this is when I bucked him on this.
This is really what started this matter in the soup.
Oh, I see.
In other words, he wanted to build one apartment unit there using the street as a parking area.
You know, building the apartment right out to the street.
And I said, I wouldn't go along with that.
He ought to provide for off-street parking.
And that's really started.
Was that after, when was that?
When I was mayor.
And was he on council?
Yeah.
He was still on council?
Yeah, that was the prelude, you know, to a lot of this other...
Okay.
How did the council, when you were on council, feel about planning?
I know that the graduate period plan was put into effect, but how effective was that?
Well, this was an attempt on the part of the county highway department and the two cities to evolve a long-range program, a plan that we could follow.
Any plan, however, is subject to revision.
This is my comment with some certain people at the university now.
It's all right to say that now the city's going to grow this way and therefore I should be planned accordingly.
But then suppose the city starts to grow this way, what are you going to do?
After your plan is, you know.
You can't get a plan that is 100% perfect.
We had this particular plan and I thought it did us very well for at least five years or more.
And then there was a lot of interest in gender within the two cities to make their own comprehensive plans.
So, actually, Brad's area plan was not... Well, we used it as a guide.
I think I still have copies of it around someplace.
They haven't stopped the city, I guess.
Well, I haven't seen it in mine, but I have.
Well, I don't think I threw them out.
I think I still have, because I was vice president of the board when the last of them met.
And...
But it was a forerunner to what the cities eventually then, you know, took over and decided to expand on their own.
Now there was, as you probably know, there was some hard feelings between Bryan and College Station over the years.
And it is still evident today.
I still run into it.
But I can cite well
These things didn't help the community grow together, you know, county-wise in two cities.
Well, the plan was good for what it was intended to be.
And it served as a guide to our city for two years.
Oh, I say over five years.
And then we began to expand on it on our own and develop our own long-range plan.
And the city of Bryan attempted to do the same thing.
One divorced pretty much from the other.
Now they may say that they tried to coordinate, and they did to some extent, but each of them I think went off on their own in many areas.
I remember
For example, we had a fellow come in here and set up a taxi, a stand, across from Ramona.
And the radio controls of his office, very nice, one-man outfit.
And he called me one day and he was arrested in crime.
I said, arrested for what?
He said, because I can't take passengers into crime from the airport.
And I said, you don't say.

So I called up Brian, and I just told him, the mayor and Brian, that in fact, tomorrow morning, I gave orders to our police to stop every Brian taxi that came into College Station because of violation of our ordinance.
And they said, Eddie, what are they violating?
I said, they're violating our ordinance.
That's all I'm going to say.
And they think that tomorrow morning they'll do it.
Now, I'm doing this because our man was thus and so and so.
And boy, they got on the phone and all of them down there.
Well, but the next day it was all settled.
That was when you were mayor?
Yeah.
Well, it was just one of the incidents.
One of many, yeah.
So the Brazos area plan was...
a plan for the overall county?
Is it like a transportation?
Right, the highway department and all of them were involved.
And hopefully it was to help the cities.
The two cities and the county as a whole.
Grow together.
Grow together and plan together.
But in fact they didn't.
Well they didn't, not to the extent that they should have.
To my knowledge, I don't know whether the Razzis Area Incorporation still exists or not.
They had a charter, and I know I was vice president the last time we met, and the thing just naturally dissipated.
Do you remember when it dissipated?
I think it was, I guess it was, they started talking about it in the early 60s, and it lasted about five years.
Oh yeah, yeah.
and uh let's see what's the butler r.b butler the senior was uh president i think oh yeah we we were but uh
And it eventually evolved.
I think the stimuli, too, came from the university to do, you know, more planning.
And the Planning and Zoning Commission then took a more active role than it had in the past.
And that led, of course, to all the things that in late years developed, you know, in terms of planning.
The previous years, I guess it was more of a competition with slow but steady growth.
Yeah, that's right.
It didn't have the growth that, you know, it was just, you get a slow growth.
Then when we began really to expand and grow more at a faster pace, things changed.
Yeah.
To a great deal.
You know, that's what this meeting was about today, in part.
What's going to happen to this industrial country between you and I?
Are you aware of it?
The industrial development out there?
Well, somebody's got wind, and it's going to be huge.
Thank you.
Oh, I'll have to be there.
Well, I don't come for it.
Oh, no, no, sir.
I won't.
Oh, and I don't write for the papers either.
Well, there's no confidentiality about us here.
But I am privy to a lot of stuff by a lot of people.
The Telman thing.
So when Andy, you know, it's off the record.
Right.
And because I respect him, I hear more.
You know what I mean?
I can get out of the courthouse
And I start down with the girl down there, the secretary down there, you know, the commissioner.

Chat with them all down there, you know, and they'd go in and think of getting the commissioner to go and go see the sheriff, who's a friend of mine, and then start upstairs, you know, chat with the JPs and the county judge, you know what I mean, and all the rest of them.
